content.text:
Here is what was going on and what we changed.

**Cause:** The outer wrapper of `BottomTabBar` is taller than the drawn bar (`barH + insets.bottom`) so the home-indicator area is filled with a solid color. That color was `TAB_BAR_GRADIENT.color1` (`#222834`), the **dark end** of the tab gradient. Your screens use `COLORS.bg` (`#242C3B`), which is **lighter**, so the strip under the SVG looked like a darker gray band “behind” the bar.

**Change:** Use `COLORS.bg` for that outer fill so the inset zone matches the stack / Discover background. The SVG gradient for the bar itself is unchanged.

```184:198:c:\Users\debob\Desktop\GymBros TakeHome\components\BottomTabBar.tsx
  return (
    <View
      style={[
        {
          height:           layoutH,
          width,
          // Match screen bg under the home inset — `color1` is the gradient’s darker stop (#222834)
          // and reads as a seam vs `COLORS.bg` (#242C3B).
          backgroundColor: COLORS.bg,
        },
        styles.outer,
        style,
      ]}
    >
```

If you ever want that zone to match the **bottom** of the tab gradient instead (e.g. on a screen with a different background), you could sample that color or use a token aligned to the gradient’s lower edge; for this app, `COLORS.bg` matches `_layout` and Discover’s `styles.safe`.

